ce:section.ce:para:
Thresholds (

                                 t

                           ) temper targets by introducing minimal values that countries should never go below in the case of ‘goods’ indicators, and maximal values that countries should never go above in the case of ‘bads’ indicators. Thresholds are planetary boundaries common to all countries or all countries in an economic development group. They are determined either by internationally accepted scientific sources, such as the threshold limit for air pollution indicators, or they are empirically derived. For example, there is no scientific evidence for determining an appropriate value for the indicator MVA in GDP. In such cases, thresholds are determined empirically in the same way used for some of the 13 indicators in the GEP index. For ‘good’ indicators, the threshold is set at the 25th percentile of the distribution in the initial year, and for ‘bads’ indicators, it is set at the 75th percentile in the initial year. Hence, countries should not go below or achieve less than the point that is achieved by the bottom 25 percent of countries for ‘goods’ indicators in the initial year. Conversely, no country should go above or increase more than the top 75 percent of countries for ‘bads’ indicators in the initial year.
